label.value: envenomation resulting in modulation of complement activation, classical pathway in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the regulation of complement activation via the classical pathway of the bitten/stung organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in negative regulation of complement activation, classical pathway in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the negative regulation of complement activation via the classical pathway of the bitten/stung organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in positive regulation of complement activation, classical pathway in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the positive regulation of complement activation via the classical pathway of the bitten/stung organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in modulation of complement activation, lectin pathway in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the resultant modulation of complement activation via the lectin pathway in the bitten/stung organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in negative regulation of complement activation, lectin pathway in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the resultant negative regulation of complement activation via the lectin pathway in the bitten/stung organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in positive regulation of complement activation, lectin pathway in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the resultant positive regulation of complement activation via the lectin pathway in the bitten/stung organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in modulation of complement activation, alternative pathway in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the resultant modulation of complement activation via the alternative pathway in the bitten/stung organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in positive regulation of complement activation, alternative pathway in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the resultant positive regulation of complement activation via the alternative pathway in the bitten/stung organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in negative regulation of complement activation, alternative pathway in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the resultant negative regulation of complement activation via the alternative pathway in the bitten/stung organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in modulation of complement activation in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the resultant modulation of complement activation in the bitten/stung organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in cytolysis in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with cytolysis in the bitten organism.
The specific behavior of an organism that is associated with reproduction involving another organism of the same or different species.

label.value: envenomation resulting in modulation of acid-sensing ion channel activity in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with a resultant change in the activity of an acid-sensing ion channel (ASIC) in the bitten organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in positive regulation of acid-sensing ion channel activity in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with a resultant positive regulation in the activity of an acid-sensing ion channel (ASIC) in the bitten organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in negative regulation of acid-sensing ion channel activity in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with a resultant negative regulation in the activity of an acid-sensing ion channel (ASIC) in the bitten organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in negative regulation of sensory perception of pain in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the inhibition of the sensory perception of pain in the bitten organism.

label.value: envenomation resulting in modulation of sensory perception of pain in other organism

definition.value: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the modulation of the sensory perception of pain in the bitten organism.
The specific behavior of an organism following mating.

label.value: male courtship behavior, veined wing generated song production

definition.value: The process during wing vibration where the male insect produces a species-specific acoustic signal called a love song.

label.value: negative regulation of female receptivity, post-mating

definition.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the receptiveness of a female to male advances subsequent to mating.
The rhythm of the locomotor activity of an organism during its 24 hour activity cycle.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the willingness or readiness of a female to receive male advances.
Any process that activates or increases the receptiveness of a female to male advances.
Any process that modulates the receptiveness of a female to male advances subsequent to mating.

label.value: positive regulation of female receptivity, post-mating

definition.value: Any process that increases the receptiveness of a female to male advances subsequent to mating.

A simple form of learning whereby the repeated presence of a stimulus leads to a change in the probability or strength of the response to that stimulus. There is no association of one type of stimulus with another, rather it is a generalized response to the environment.
A decrease in a behavioral response to a repeated stimulus. This is exemplified by the failure of a person to show a startle response to a loud noise that has been repeatedly presented.

An increased in a behavioral response to a repeated stimulus. For example, a shock to the tail of the marine snail Aplysia, to which the snail responds by withdrawing its gill, will result in increased gill withdrawal the next time the skin is touched.
The behavior of individuals for the purpose of discriminating between the sexes, for the purpose of finding a suitable mating partner.

label.value: male courtship behavior, veined wing extension

definition.value: The process during courtship where the male insect extends his wings. An example of this process is found in Drosophila melanogaster.
Any process that results in a change in the behavior of an organism as a result of a cocaine stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in the behavior of an organism as a result of an ethanol stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in the behavior of an organism as a result of an ether stimulus.

Any process that results in a change in the behavior of an organism as a result of a pain stimulus. Pain stimuli cause activation of nociceptors, peripheral receptors for pain, include receptors which are sensitive to painful mechanical stimuli, extreme heat or cold, and chemical stimuli.
The specific behavior of an organism that recurs with a regularity of approximately 24 hours.
The part of the circadian sleep/wake cycle where the organism is asleep.
Any process in which an organism has a behavioral effect on another organism of the same or different species.
Any process that results in a change in the behavior of an organism as a result of a nutrient stimulus.
The set of behavioral processes that occur as part of the general adaptation syndrome, the response of the body to a strong, stressful stimulus.
The specific behavior of a male organism that is associated with reproduction.
The specific behavior of a female organism that is associated with reproduction.
The behavior in which an organism sheds tears, often accompanied by non-verbal vocalizations and in response to external or internal stimuli.
The deposition of eggs, either fertilized or not, upon a surface or into a medium, following mating.
A reproductive behavior in which a parent cares for and rears offspring.
A parental behavior in which fertilized eggs are taken into the mouth and held until hatching.
Behavior by which an organism locates food.
Behavior by which an adult locates food.
Foraging behavior in which an anatomical part of the organism is inserted into the substrate to locate food.
Any process that results in a change in the behaviour of an organism as a result of a chemical pain stimulus.

label.value: behavioral response to acetic acid induced pain

definition.value: Any process that results in a change in the behaviour of an organism as a result of an acetic acid pain stimulus.
